    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-14T18:00:00-05:00" n="133"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d133">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/1708: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile (<persName corresp="#p_CWS1"
                            type="from">Culbertson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 14, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. Referring to the Department’s telegram No. 18, April 8, 1 p.m.<note n="96"
                        xml:id="d133fn96">Not printed.</note> and circular telegram relating to
                    Chaco April 13, 6 p.m., the following is the result of conversation with Foreign
                    Minister this afternoon: <list>
                        <item>First. If the five neutrals invite Chile, Argentina, Brazil and Peru
                            to cooperate in the interests of peace, Chile will accept.</item>
                        <item>Second. Relating to Chile’s treaty with Bolivia, Minister said “the
                                <pb facs="0242" n="138" xml:id="pg_138"/> treaty of 1904<note n="97"
                                xml:id="d133fn97">Signed at Santiago, October 20, 1904, <ref
                                    target="frus1905#pg_104">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1905, p.
                                104</ref>.</note> is in force and Chile is obliged and determined to
                            comply with it. In accordance with the said treaty, under present
                            conditions Chile could not prevent the transit through its territory of
                            arms for Bolivia. If a state of war should subsequently be produced
                            between Bolivia and Paraguay, Chile would consider such a new situation
                            in order to act on it in accord with its international
                            obligations”.</item>
                        <item>Third. Minister stated that <persName corresp="#p_CTM1"
                                >Cruchaga</persName> would receive instructions tomorrow to express
                            Chile’s agreement with suggestion made in the statement of the neutrals
                            last Monday. No comment in press.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
